<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Receives Deputy Secretary Talbott </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa Receives Deputy Secretary Talbott </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104094694 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0757 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 11 Apr (PAP)--A period of confrontation in 
Europe has not been followed by major changes. There is a 
chance for a peaceful solution of problems, but swift actions 
and brave decisions are needed. The United States has the 
greatest responsibility for the future, President Lech Walesa 
said today, when greeting U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe 
Talbott at the Belweder Palace. 
  According to the president, a chance exists for building 
unity in Europe, and, "acting together with the United States, 
we might achieve splendid victories." "It is the United States 
that is the most important in the battleground at present," Lech 
Walesa said. Poland is concerned with the remnants of communism 
and the Warsaw Pact, although, according to the president, there 
are no major threats. 
  Lech Walesa underscored that West Europe maintains its 
position and NATO is not expanding. "We have been struggling 
for 50 years with millions of victims and great financial 
costs," he said. Poland has devoted the past four years to the 
search. No great structural changes have been made, and life 
cannot stand a vacuum, Lech Walesa argued. 

</TEXT>

