<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Butrus-Ghali Threatens Air Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> AU0904134294 Paris AFP in English 1336 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0904134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 9 (AFP) -- UN chief Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali Saturday ordered UN forces in Bosnia to use "all 
available means" to obtain the withdrawal of Bosnian Serb troops 
threatening the Moslem enclave of Gorazde. 
  Butrus-Ghali said in a statement released by his spokeswoman 
Therese Gastaut that the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] in 
former Yugoslavia must "use all available means as authorized by 
the relevant Security Council resolutions to attain this 
objective." 
  Gastaut said the resolutions included the possible recourse 
to NATO air strikes because Gorazde was a protected UN "safe 
haven". 
  The statement was issued as the Bosnian Serbs seized 
strategic high ground overlooking Gorazde as part of a 10-day 
offensive on the Moslem pocket in eastern Bosnia. 
  In his statement, Butrus-Ghali welcomed ``the positive 
momentum and progress towards peace and stability in the former 
Yugoslavia. 
  ``With regard to the safe area of Gorazde, the 
Secretary-General has taken note of the improvement in the 
situation there which was reported to him this (Saturday) 
morning. 
  "At the same time, he calls for a return by the parties, 
especially the Bosnian Serbs, to the positions they held before 
the outbreak of the recent fighting." 
  The statement was issued after the UN chief held meetings in 
Geneva earlier on Saturday with his special representative to 
former Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, as well as UN mediator 
Thorvald Stoltenberg, Sarajevo special coordinator William 
Eagleton and UNPROFOR chief General Bertrand de Sauville de 
Lapresle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

