<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Cease-Fire Talks Break Down </H4>

<F P=102> AU0904153894 Paris AFP in English 1539 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0904153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, April 9 (AFP) -- Ceasefire talks 
between Bosnian and Bosnian Serb military leaders at Sarajevo 
airport broke down Saturday afternoon minutes after getting 
under way, the UN said. 
  Bosnian general Rasim Delic and Bosnian Serb general Ratko 
Mladic will now have a 48-hour cooling off period during which 
they will both hold consultations with political authorities, 
said United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) commander in 
Bosnia, General Michael Rose. 
  The meeting was called to reach an agreement on a ceasefire 
for the eastern Bosnian Moslem enclave of Gorazde, where the 
Serbs launched a major offensive two weeks ago, and on ways of 
securing a global solution to the Bosnia crisis. 
  But Delic insisted on a "short-term arrangement" for Gorazde 
while the Bosnian Serbs were seeking an overall ceasefire, 
UNPROFOR spokesman Captain Eric Chaperon said. [passage omitted] 
  Despite the breakdown, the UNPROFOR spokesman said Rose 
remained confident an agreement would eventually be signed. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

