<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Welcomes NATO Action Against Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Welcomes NATO Action Against Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104151494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104151494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a statement by the Croatian Foreign 
Ministry, the Croatian Government welcomed the resolute NATO 
action against the military positions of the Bosnian Serbs 
around the besieged Muslim enclave, that is, the protected area 
of Gorazde. 
  The Croatian Government believes that the air strikes 
against 
the Serb military positions around Gorazde are a legitimate and 
justified action in support of the implementation of UNPROFOR's 
[UN Protection Force] mandate in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The 
statement stresses the fact that the action followed a blatant 
violation by Serbs of all UN Security Council resolutions and 
statements on the protection of Gorazde, and was in keeping with 
a plan of action jointly elaborated by the United Nations and 
NATO. 
  Besides the immediate effect of stopping Serb advances on 
central Gorazde, and averting danger to the town and tens of 
thousands of civilians and refugees, the NATO action undoubtedly 
has a symbolic significance. The NATO air strikes carried out 
by U.S. fighter-jets shows that, despite the complexity of 
international coordination mechanisms, it is possible to reach 
an effective consent at short notice, and that the international 
community has enough legitimately adopted documents, measures 
and responses to counter violators of international norms. 
  The Croatian Government therefore considers the Gorazde 
action to be the last warning of the international community and 
a call to certain forces among the Serbian people to stop 
military activities, blatant violations of international norms 
and agreements, and to join serious negotiations, in order to 
find a solution acceptable to all sides and to restore peace, 
stability, and security in this part of Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8129 </DOCNO>
