<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Woerner Cited on Gorazde Strike, Damage Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Woerner Cited on Gorazde Strike, Damage Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104160894 Paris AFP in English 1518 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1104160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, April 11 (AFP) -- A U.S. jet fighter 
apparently destroyed three tanks Monday [11 April] during the 
second NATO attack in less than 24 hours on Serb positions 
around the mainly Moslem town of Gorazde in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
NATO said here. Manfred Woerner, secretary-general of the North 
Atlantic Treaty Organisation, said a single U.S. FA-18A jet 
fighter carried out the strike. 
  "We have only first pilot reports, which say that three 
tanks 
seem to have been destroyed but that is not confirmed," he said 
in a statement. The attack occurred at 1224 GMT. 
  On Sunday [10 April] two U.S. F-16 aircraft dropped five 
bombs on a Serb artillery position outside Gorazde, a Moslem 
enclave being besieged by Serb forces which is under United 
Nations protection as an officially-designated safe area. 
  The operation was officially launched in support of UN 
personnel at Goradze. Bosnian Serbs fired more shells on the 
town on Monday, reportedly injuring 200 people at a refugee 
centre. Woerner said: "Serbs had resumed shelling from the 
south and UN personnel trapped in the area were in some danger." 
  On Sunday, after the first strike, U.S. President Bill 
Clinton warned that U.S. warplanes would strike again in Bosnia 
if UN authorities asked for military support. Sunday's attack 
was the first by NATO warplanes on Serb ground positions since 
the civil war in Bosnia began two years ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8147 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070aa_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

