<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN `Surprised' About NATO Planes at Tuzla </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN `Surprised' About NATO Planes at Tuzla </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204100494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0907 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1204100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] New York, April 12 (TANJUG) -- No one at the United 
Nations headquarters could confirm or deny on Tuesday reports 
that a NATO aircraft bringing special troops and war equipment 
had landed at Tuzla airport in eastern Bosnia. 
  The report surprised even U.N. peace missions spokesman Fred 
Eckhard. He told TANJUG that he did not know anything about it, 
but that it was possible that the report was correct and that 
the troops and equipment involved could be those intended for 
securing the airport. 
  The Bosnian Serb army general staff accused NATO on Monday 
of 
having used its aircraft for a synchronized action with Bosnian 
Moslem infantry against Serb positions at Gorazde and of having 
brought its rapid deployment force units to Tuzla airport. 
  The Bosnian Serb army general staff also said a NATO C-130 
transport aircraft landed at Tuzla's Dubrava airport at 16:50 
hrs local time on Monday, bringing members of the NATO Rapid 
Deployment Force and a considerable quantity of ammunition, 
weapons and military equipment for a coordinated action with 
Bosnian Moslem units against Bosnian Serb units. 
  The synchronized attack in the Gorazde area and the use of 
the Tuzla airport for military purposes (the airport has not 
been reopened for relief aid deliveries yet) indicates that the 
U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) has overstepped its mandate and 
that it will be fully responsible if the conflicts in former 
Bosnia- Herzegovina escalate, the general staff said. 
  Bosnian Serbs have opposed the reopening of Tuzla airport, 
justly fearing that it might be used as a conduit for supplying 
Moslem units with military equipment. They have demanded that 
Serb observers and Russian peacekeepers be deployed at the 
airport. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

