<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Comments on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Comments on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104193094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1903 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 11 Apr (TANJUG) -- Special Russian envoy 
Vitaliy Churkin said after the talks with Srpska republic 
president Radovan Karadzic in Pale this evening that "ways are 
being sought to restore the peace negotiations and to find a 
political solution to the current crisis." 
  President Karadzic said Russian diplomats would try to 
bridge 
the current gap between the Serb side and the UN Protection 
Forces [UNPROFOR]. 
  The talks between Churkin and Karadzic lasted almost an 
hour. 
The Russian envoy said he was immediately leaving for Sarajevo, 
where he should meet UNPROFOR officials. 
  "I hope to return [to Pale] this evening to resume talks 
with 
president Karadzic," Churkin added. 
  Srpska republic president Radovan Karadzic told reporters 
that the previous crisis (NATO ultimatum on 20 February) had 
been successfully resolved owing to Churkin. 
  "However, now we do not know how to find a way out of this 
situation, but we know for certain that UNPROFOR has abused the 
presence of UN representatives,, blamed the Serbs for the 
attacks, and bombed our positions," Karadzic said. 
  "We do not see how we can cooperate with UNPROFOR when they 
have sided with one of the sides in the civil war. However, the 
Russian diplomacy will try to bridge the gap between us and 
UNPROFOR," Karadzic said. 
  It is expected that talks between Karadzic and Churkin will 
be resumed later this evening after the Russian envoy returns 
from the Muslim part of Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

