<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic: Air Strikes `Not Enough' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic: Air Strikes `Not Enough' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104205494 Berlin N-TV in German 2000 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104205494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin N-TV </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Excerpts] This afternoon NATO aircraft attacked Serb 
positions near the eastern Bosnian town of Gorazde for the 
second time in 24 hours. [passage omitted] 
  In the N-TV "Newspunkt" program, Bosnian Prime Minister 
Haris 
Silajdzic commented on the NATO air strikes on Serb positions. 
  [Haris Silajdzic, in English, with superimposed German 
translation] "The principle is right but unfortunately it is not 
enough. This is not enough of a deterrent. Unfortunately there 
was too much hesitation, and then when finally intervention 
came, it was only half-hearted. Although we really welcome the 
work of NATO and the United Nations, it is still not enough. I 
think a not very strong message was sent there, not strong 
enough." 
  [Announcer] To the question of what more had to be done, 
Silajdzic told N-TV: 
  [Silajdzic] "As far as I know, two or three tanks were 
destroyed in these attacks. Serb soldiers, however, destroyed 
far more than 10 Bosnian tanks and the people in them. The 
lesson is not yet hard enough. A clear lesson would be to 
destroy all the Serbs' tanks, that is the only way. A clear 
message would be to lift the arms embargo against the Bosnians. 
As you know we have been denied this so far. The international 
community owes us this, however. Then we can deal with our own 
defense. Let us defend ourselves and we will do it ourselves." 

</TEXT>

