<H3> <TI>   Karadzic To `Help' Muslims Following Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic To `Help' Muslims Following Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204125294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1048 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204125294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 12 Apr (TANJUG) -- I have to say that NATO 
bombarded the center of Gorazde, its Muslim part, with horrible 
consequences -- a large number of people were killed in this 
attack, Srpska republic president Radovan Karadzic said this 
morning following his talks with Russian envoy Vitaliy Churkin. 
  I am going to visit Gorazde to find out as to how we can 
help 
the Muslim civilians in a most effective way since NATO is 
bombing both sides, Karadzic said as he was setting off for 
Gorazde. 
  The president of the Srpska republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
met Vitaliy Churkin, Russia's deputy minister for foreign 
affairs late last night following the latter's visit to the 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] command in Sarajevo. The talks 
continued this morning, although no major success has been 
achieved. 
  Churkin's idea was to organize a meeting of Karadzic, 
Yasushi 
Akashi, and Charles Redman, the U.S. President's special envoy 
for the former Yugoslavia, but this initiative was met with no 
enthusiasm on the part of the leadership of the Srpska republic, 
TANJUG has learned from reliable sources. 
  The question of what to discuss, and how, with those 
officials who had taken an active part in taking the decision to 
bomb Serb territories remains the main obstacle. 

</TEXT>

