<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says UN Violated Charter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says UN Violated Charter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104191794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1840 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 11 (TANJUG) -- Assembly President of 
the Bosnian Serb Republic (R.S.) Momcilo Krajisnik on Monday 
said the renewed air strikes against Bosnian Serb positions on 
Monday were a disastrous move on the part of the United Nations, 
which he said had greatly exceeded its authority and assigned 
NATO the task out of a wish to aid the Bosnian Muslims in their 
offensive in the area of Gorazde. 
  "We had proposed that the war stop on all of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina territory, but the proposal was not upheld by 
either the Muslims or the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR), but, 
quite the contrary, the Muslim offensive was tolerated and 
(Bosnian) Serb positions were air raided," Krajisnik said on 
Belgrade's Politika TV. 
  The Muslim side in late March launched a strong offensive on 
Bosnian Serb positions from Gorazde, a Muslim enclave which 
should have been demilitarized last spring as a U.N.-proclaimed 
"safe area." around 10,000 Muslim troops were massed for the 
offensive. 
  Krajisnik said that the Serb side countered the Muslim 
offensive because it was provoked and because the Muslims used 
the "safe area," which has not territorially been defined, "as a 
source of war" in eastern Bosnia. 
  The R.S. assembly president said that UNPROFOR had for no 
reason at all violated the U.N. charter and its mandate in 
Bosnia- Herzegovina, and instead of censuring the Muslims had 
"completely sided with the Serb enemies." 
  Krajisnik said that the R.S. leadership was following the 
situation and that it had requested of the United Nations to say 
who had ordered the air strikes. 
  Krajisnik said that the R.S. leadership would decide on its 
further action and contacts with UNPROFOR, which he said had 
been frozen for the time being, only upon receiving an answer 
from the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

