<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Mine Roads to Sarajevo Arms Depots </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Mine Roads to Sarajevo Arms Depots </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204063494 Paris AFP in English 2348 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1204063494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 12 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs closed 
checkpoints out of Sarajevo and mined access roads leading to 
arms depots guarded by UN troops Monday as tension mounted 
following NATO airstrikes on Serb positions near the Moslem 
enclave of Gorazde. 
  The mines were layed during the day outside at least three 
arms depots where Serbs had earlier placed their heavy weapons 
under UN control. Two depots were located north of the city at 
Vogosca and Radava and one, to the west, near Blazuj, a UN 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) spokesman said. 
  UNPROFOR had suspended all movement of its forces, spokesman 
Rob Annink said. 
  Meanwhile, all checkpoints leading to the city were closed 
and even the head of UNPROFOR, French general Bertrand de 
Lapresle, had to skirt around a Serb-held area to reach Sarajevo 
airport from where he flew to Zagreb. 
  An attempt to organize a meeting between De Lapresle and 
Serb 
commander General Ratko Mladic was called off after Bosnian 
Serbs broke off all contacts with UNPROFOR Sunday night in the 
wake of a first North Atlantic Treaty Organisation air strike 
against their forces outside besieged Gorazde. A second strike 
was carried out Monday. 
  The UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Monday 
suspended its air bridge to Sarajevo and a spokeswoman said 
UNHCR would reassess the situation Tuesday before deciding 
whether to resume airlifts of injured Bosnians out of Sarajevo 
to the Italian airforce base at Ancona. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

