<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Criticizes UN for Launching Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Criticizes UN for Launching Air Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104123394 Paris AFP in English 1209 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1104123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 11 (AFP) -- Russia's special envoy 
to ex-Yugoslavia Vitaliy Churkin criticized the United Nations 
Monday for launching air strikes against Serb positions in 
Gorazde saying that the international community had embarked on 
a "slippery slope" in Bosnia. 
  "We are very much concerned that maybe we are on a slippery 
slope in terms of international involvement in this fighting 
area, and our main effort now will be directed at making sure 
that this tragic experience of Gorazde is not going to be 
repeated," Churkin told reporters here after holding a two-hour 
meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic. 
  He said Milosevic had asked him to try "to help find a way 
out of this situation" which has been rendered more difficult by 
the Bosnian Serb decision to break all contact with the UN 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR). 
  Churkin said he believed Russia could play an important role 
in relaunching the peace process which would be aimed at finding 
a "firm and lasting cessation of hostilities." 
  He said Russia was not pleased at the "level of 
communication 
in this very tense moment," apparently referring to the UN 
decision to launch the air strikes without consulting with 
Russia first. 
  "I believe that if Russia was involved in a much closer way 
in this conflict area, maybe some of the developments may have 
been prevented," he said. 
  Churkin was to travel to the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale 
later Monday to meet with military leader Radovan Karadzic. The 
latter earlier cancelled a meeting with U.S. special envoy to 
ex-Yugoslavia Charles Redman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

