<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY Delegation To Visit Srpska Republic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FRY Delegation To Visit Srpska Republic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104144394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1317 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 11 Apr (TANJUG) -- At its session today 
the federal government discussed the situation in the wake of 
the NATO air strike against the territory of the Srpska republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina in the vicinity of Gorazde. It decided to 
send a delegation of the Yugoslav Government, headed by Vice 
Prime Minister Zeljko Simic, to the Srpska republic where they 
will acquaint themselves with the situation and consequences on 
the spot. 
  The government, as is reported, also decided to send a 
protest note to Italy, because it provided its air bases for the 
aircraft that attacked the Serb territories in 
ex-Bosnia-Herzegovina. At the same time it decided that the 
federal government would send a letter to UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali in which it will point out the facts that indicate 
that the NATO air strike against the territory of the Srpska 
republic was a violation of the UN Charter. 

</TEXT>

