<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Simic To Head Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Simic To Head Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104160794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1537 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 11 (TANJUG) -- A delegation of the 
Yugoslav Federal Government, headed by Deputy Prime Minister 
Zeljko Simic, will visit the Srpska republic in order to look 
into the consequences of the NATO plane bombardment there. 
  The government brought this decision at an extraordinary 
session Monday [11 April] devoted to the situation following the 
bombardment of the Srpska republic around the town of Gorazde, 
in the east of war-shattered Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The government has also decided to address a protest note to 
Italy for having allowed NATO planes to fly from its airfields 
and a letter to the UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
pointing out that the NATO air attacks on the Srpska republic 
constitute a violation of the U.N charter, it is said in a 
statement issued by the government. 
  At the same session the government has assessed the U.N. 
decision about the engagement of NATO airforces in the 
bombardment of the territory of the Srpska republic as direct 
involvement in the civil war in Bosnia-Herzegovina on the side 
of the Moslems and a dangerous precedent which could have 
far-reaching consequences. 
  The cabinet of Prime Minister Kontic has also conveyed the 
solidarity of all Yugoslav citizens with the Serb people in the 
Srpska republic who are the victims of aggression. 
  The U.N. has brought the decision about the engagement of 
NATO planes at the request of the peacekeepers on the field who 
accused the Serbs of attacking the civilian population in 
Gorazde. 
  According to Serb military sources, however, it was from 
Gorazde that around 10,000 Moslem troops launched an attack on 
Serb positions around the town, which should have been 
demilitarized last spring as a UN-protected area. 
  Reports of the U.N. peackeepers confirm that the combats 
around Gorazde were provoked by the Moslems. According to Serb 
military sources the Moslem offensive is aimed at gaining as 
much territory as possible from the Serbs ahead of the 
continuation of the peace talks conducted under international 
mediation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

