<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa, Pawlak, Olechowski Meet With Talbott </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa, Pawlak, Olechowski Meet With Talbott </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104181094 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Strobe Talbott, U.S. deputy secretary of state, who 
is on an official visit to Poland, has been received by 
President Lech Walesa and Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak. He 
also had a one-hour conversation with Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski. 
  After years of confrontation and polarization, Walesa said 
in 
greeting the U.S. guest, there is now a chance to build a new 
order in Europe. We have fought for 50 years for Europe without 
divisions. This has cost millions of victims; the financial 
costs were enormous. After the sophisticated struggle in the 
1980's, there is now a chance to resolve the problems. Fast 
action and courageous decisions are needed, the president said. 
  [Begin Walesa recording] I am convinced that, by cooperating 
with the United States, we can achieve beautiful victories in 
Europe. We are, however, concerned about the remnants of 
communism and the Warsaw Treaty. Of course, there are no direct 
dangers, but a sphere under a question mark still remains. We 
wonder whether this sphere, when left alone, can rebuild the old 
setup in different conditions but following the communist 
pattern, or whether one should aim at unity in Europe. [sentence 
as heard] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8227 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070_p_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak, Olechowski Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pawlak, Olechowski Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104193194 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting between Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak and 
the U.S. deputy secretary of state, which lasted almost an hour 
and a half, concentrated on Polish-U.S. cooperation. Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak said after the talks: 
  [Begin Pawlak recording] We talked with Secretary Talbott 
about the internal situation in Poland. I presented a report 
about our economic indicators for the first quarter. Inflation, 
which is at its lowest for the past seven years, and a 
considerable increase in industrial output are worth noting here. 
  We also talked about cooperation within various 
international 
organizations, starting with financial institutions like the 
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund and also those 
that speed up various ways of development, among them GATT and 
the EBRD [European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]. 
  Discussion of the Partnership for Peace program played a 
very 
important part in our talks. Further talks on this matter will 
take place between experts so that practical, concrete, and 
joint projects can be initiated this year. I think that the 
development of our region, Central Europe, is also very 
important. We discussed how the development of Europe can be 
supported in an efficient and effective way. [end recording] 
  It has transpired from brief statements made by Deputy 
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Polish Foreign Minister 
Andrzej Olechowski that their talks focused on the philosophy of 
the Partnership for Peace program. Partnership for Peace, 
Minister Olechowski said, is an instrument that could result in 
a Europe without divisions, or in a new division of Europe. He 
added that this opinion was shared by his U.S. guest. Our 
efforts in implementing the idea of the Partnership of Peace 
program, Minister Olechowski said, go in the direction of 
possibilities for cooperation between Poland's and NATO's 
defense systems. The objective is that, if need be, these 
systems should be able to cooperate with each other at any time. 
  Minister Olechowski added that there would be visible 
evidence of this partnership and that there would be more joint 
exercises and joint actions. Journalists asked Minister 
Olechowski whether this visit would change anything in our 
mutual relations. 
  [Begin recording] [Olechowski] No, I do not think so. I 
think that the nature of this visit.... [pauses] Mr. Talbott is 
a man with vivid interests, he is intellectually alert, and he 
promised to come to Poland on his first visit. I think that he 
wanted to show that he is interested not only in Russia. That 
is why he came to Poland to listen to what we have to say. We 
have heard the most recent opinions. I do not see any great 
differences here with what I heard three months ago. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Specifically, can you name any 
undertakings with regard to the Partnership for Peace? 
  [Olechowski] There is our program, the presentation 
document, 
that we shall submit to Brussels very soon. We can see that 
this document, which has been written according to the 
philosophy I have described, is being favorably received. 
  We also talked about President Clinton's visit. He is to 
visit us in July. We talked about our region, and we shall 
continue this conversation this evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8228 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070_i_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Raids on `Serbian Territory' Protested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Raids on `Serbian Territory' Protested </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104160194 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1104160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Marica Lalovic from Pale] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Vitaliy Churkin, special 
Russian envoy, is expected to arrive in Pale at 1630. He will 
have talks with the state leadership of the Srpska republic 
about the latest events concerning Gorazde and a possible 
resumption of the peace negotiations, for which the UN forces 
bear further responsibility, it is said in the announcement of 
the supreme command of the Srpska republic. The announcement 
further says that a harsh protest is being issued for raiding 
Serbian territory around Gorazde, stressing that with this 
gesture, the UN has openly taken the side against Serbs in this 
civil war in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina. The supreme command 
of the Srpska republic warns that politically motivated elements 
in NATO and the United Nations are encouraging Muslim attacks, 
so that they can take advantage of a Serbian response as an 
excuse for a military intervention. However, Serbs will not be 
frightened and they will retain the right to self-defense with 
all available weapons, it is said in the announcement by the 
supreme command. 
  There are still no precise reports on what is really 
happening around Tarcin. However, the situation is still 
extremely tense because Muslim radio [Sarajevo Radio] is no 
longer concealing the fact that several hundred Muslim refugees 
from eastern Bosnia have occupied the prison in Tarcin and 
kidnapped three Serbian inmates from it. The Tarcin prison has 
been blocked since Friday and it is threatened that all Serbs in 
it will be killed if the alleged shelling of Gorazde does not 
stop. The Serbian side has been demanding the closing down of 
Tarcin prison for some time now, but Muslim representatives have 
persistently refused, although at the Geneva conference they 
signed an agreement to release all prisoners under their control. 
  By the way, all humanitarian convoys and humanitarian 
flights 
on the territory of the former Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Srpska 
republic have been suspended and the Serbian civil authorities 
have closed down all the blue roads in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

