<F P=101> Albania </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO General Visits, Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO General Visits, Meets With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Briefed on Army Reform </H4>

<F P=102> AU0904170394 Tirana ATA in English 1021 GMT 9 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0904170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, April 9 (ATA) -- "The Albanian Army and 
people have a special respect for NATO as an alliance of peace 
and security," Lieutenant-General Ilia Vasho, chief of the Army 
General Staff, said in the meeting with NATO supreme commander 
and the commander-in-chief of the U.S. Forces in Europe, George 
Joulwan. Mr. Vasho described for his honoured guest the reforms 
carried out in the Albanian Army, focusing on the main tasks of 
the army to create new visions in training, improvement of 
living conditions for troops and officers, preparation of a new 
military doctrine, and upgrading the qualifications of the 
officers in contemporary military science. 
  General Joulwan said he was impressed by the great progress 
that had been made in restructuring and modernizing the army. 
He extolled the character and high qualities of the Albanian 
fighting man which, General Joulwan said, were evident both in 
his meetings with the staff at the military bases and in his 
talks with Albanian officers. General Joulwan hailed the role 
of the alliance in promoting friendship among peoples. "The 
peoples appreciate freedom, friendship and sovereignty, these 
are the values that unite mankind and which our alliance 
manifests," General Joulwan said. 
  During its stay in Tirana, the NATO delegation attended the 
inauguration of the Academy for Non-commissioned Officers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

