<H3> <TI>   Aleksandrov Repeats Stance on Troops for B-H </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aleksandrov Repeats Stance on Troops for B-H </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204113094 Sofia BTA in English 0904 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From BTA press review] </F>
  [Text] Sofia, April 12 (BTA) -- "Bulgaria's position of 
non- intervention in the developments in Sarajevo was spelled 
out by President Zhelev and Prime Minister Berov and will remain 
unchanged," STANDART NEWS quotes Defence Minister Valentin 
Aleksandrov as saying in Ankara, where he is on an official 
visit. A STANDART NEWS special correspondent reported that the 
prevailing opinion in Ankara is that the Turkish contingent to 
Sarajevo will hardly be allowed to cross Greece and Bulgaria, 
and Turkey is ready to send it by sea. 
  Quoting government sources, 24 CHASA says that U.S 
Ambassador 
to Sofia William Montgomery asked "recently" that "Turkish blue 
helmets be granted passage through Bulgaria." According to the 
daily, President Zhelev and senior diplomats had been under 
strong pressure. "Some of them were even given a hint that if 
Sofia complied, its foreign debt problems would be settled in 
the talks with the creditors of the Paris and the London Club," 
24 CHASA says. It quotes U.S. Press Attache William Cook, who 
"categorically denied yesterday that U.S. officials had attacked 
Bulgarian institutions about the passage of Turkish 
peacekeepers." 

</TEXT>

