<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Klaus' Presence Seen as `Apology' </H4>

<F P=102> AU0804181894 Prague CTK in English 1246 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804181894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 8 (CTK) -- Czech Prime Minister 
Vaclav Klaus today rejected the possibility of confrontation 
between the government and trade unions mentioned by Deputy 
Chairman of the Bohemian-Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions 
(CMKOS) Pavel Hajek in his address at the CMKOS's first congress 
today. 
  "I believe nobody is interested in confrontation," Klaus 
told 
journalists at the break in the congress, at which he delivered 
a speech. 
  CMKOS Chairman Vladimir Petrus, commenting on Klaus's 
address 
said that "he was glad to hear some of Klaus' statements, but 
had to think about others." 
  Regarding the apology which the trade union leadership 
demanded from Klaus for comparing the trade union demonstration 
on March 22 in Prague Old Town Square to the pro-communist 
demonstration from February 25, 1948, Petrus said that Klaus's 
presence at the union congress was already his apology. 
  "Klaus would have definitely not attended a conference of 
participants in a new February putsch. He came to the congress 
of his own trade unions in the Czech Republic and I personally 
fully satisfied with such an apology," Petrus said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8254 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070__a94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Unionists React to Klaus Address </H4>

<F P=102> AU0904155394 Prague CTK in English 1808 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0904155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 8 (CTK) -- The speech delivered by 
Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus at the union congress today 
did not satisfy the congress participants too much, according to 
a mini-poll conducted by CTK. 
  The delegates expressed their disapproval mainly of what 
they 
called Klaus's effort to "atomize the unions and force them 
merely to the enterprise level". The unionists already 
expressed their disapproval when Klaus was speaking. In one 
moment a slight whistle could be heard. 
  Andreas Botsch, an aide to the general secretary of the 
Trade 
Union Advisory Committee affiliated with the Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (TUAC-OECD), called Klaus's 
speech an address of a "neoliberalist economist listening with 
one ear and seeing with one eye only." Botsch was loudly 
applauded for his statement. 
  According to Botsch, Klaus said that it would be necessary 
to 
"tighten belts" even in the future. When Botsch finished his 
speech, one of the delegates proposed that his address be 
adopted as the congress's official response to Klaus's speech. 
  Some delegates expressed their displeasure at the fact that 
Klaus had not apologized for his comparing the union 
demonstration on March 22, 1994, with the communist putsch of 
February 25, 1948. 
  In the morning Vladimir Petrus, chairman of the Bohemian and 
Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions (CMKOS) said Klaus apologized 
by his participation in the congress. "Klaus would have 
definitely not attended a conference of participants in a new 
February putsch. He came to the congress of his own trade 
unions in the Czech Republic and I am personally fully satisfied 
with such an apology," Petrus said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8255 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070__a94023" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Falbr on Klaus Recommendations </H4>

<F P=102> AU0904154394 Prague CTK in English 1917 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0904154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 8 (CTK) -- Richard Falbr, one of the 
candidates for the chairmanship of the Bohemian and Moravian 
Chamber of Trade Unions (CMKOS), described as unacceptable the 
recommendations concerning the role of the unions, made by Czech 
Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus at the 1st CMKOS congress earlier 
today. 
  According to Falbr, Klaus wants the unions to work in basic 
organizations, and the union associations not to be too active 
and not to play the role of political parties. 
  Addressing the congress this morning, Klaus said that "the 
essential meaning of trade unions lies in the relationship of 
individual union members and their basic trade union 
organizations on the company level towards employers and towards 
the management of the company -- that is in the relationship on 
a micro level." 
  Falbr noted that the situation in basic organizations had 
been worsening just due to measures pushed through by the 
government and Parliament. However, Falbr did not specify the 
measures. 
  Falbr told CTK that the methods of work were exclusively the 
unions' own matter. He said that Klaus's speech was "smartly 
composed," but could not conceal the premier's ideas which are, 
according to Falbr, identical with Margaret Thatcher's negative 
view of union work. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8256 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070__a94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Union Congress Adopts New Statutes </H4>

<F P=102> AU1104120994 Prague CTK in English 2047 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 8 (CTK) -- The 1st congress of the 
Bohemian and Moravian Chamber of Trade Unions (CMKOS), after a 
stormy discussion, approved the CMKOS news statutes tonight. 
Representatives of some small trade unions even walked out of 
the negotiating room in protest against the deletion of the 
article establishing the Council of Union Chairmen. 
  The Council comprised 38 chairmen of the individual unions 
associated in the Chamber, each having one vote. 
  On the other hand, the new statutes create a new body -- the 
CMKOS Assembly, in which individual unions are represented 
proportionately to their memberships. The Assembly is to meet 
once in six months. 
  Representatives of small unions were opposed to the 
abolition 
of the Council because they are afraid of the numerical strength 
of large unions in the Assembly. Representatives of the large 
unions, on the other hand, said the Council was not functional. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8257 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070__a94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-070-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Organization Holds First Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Falbr Elected Union Chairman </H4>

<F P=102> AU1104120794 Prague CTK in English 2333 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 9 (CTK) -- Richard Falbr, 54, has 
been elected chairman of the Bohemian and Moravian Chamber of 
Trade Unions (CMKOS), it was announced officially at the CMKOS 
1st congress shortly after midnight. 
  Until now CMKOS deputy chairman, Falbr received 943 out of a 
total of 1,362 valid votes in the first round of the vote. He 
is replacing Vladimir Petrus who was elected CMKOS chairman in 
April 1990. 
  Cyril Zapletal, chairman of the Union of Mining, Geology, 
and 
Oil Workers won 150 votes, Bohumir Dufek, chairman of the 
Bohemian and Moravian Agriculture and Food Trade Union, received 
84 votes, and Karel Macura, deputy chairman of the strongest 
Kovo (metallurgy) union was supported by 61 delegates. 
  Immediately after the election, the CMKOS Assembly, 
comprising representatives from individual unions 
proportionately to their memberships, met at its constituent 
session. It is to elect four CMKOS deputy chairmen. 
  After the November 1989 "velvet revolution", Falbr became 
the 
chairman of the Bohemian-Moravian Trade Union of Service 
Workers. He briefly held the post of deputy chairman of the 
Czechoslovak Social Democratic Party (CSSD), and was the last 
head of Czechoslovakia's largest union organization, the Czech 
and Slovak Confederation of Trade Unions (CSKOS). 
  He held the post even after Czechoslovakia's split on 
January 
1, 1993, as the CSKOS continued its operation to help solve the 
problems of the labor market and joint Czech-Slovak economic 
relations. In November 1993 the CSKOS disbanded, and its two 
successors, the independent Czech (CMKOS) and Slovak chambers, 
were established. 
  Falbr continued his union activities. He contributed to the 
integration of three trade unions, those of service area, gas 
industry, and foreign trade workers, into the UNIOS trade union, 
of which he was elected chairman in mid-February 1994. 
  Falbr, a doctor of law, was born on September 29, 1940 in 
Chester, Great Britain, where his father served in the Czech air 
force unit. Falbr's mother was Spanish, which may have 
contributed to Falbr's good knowledge of foreign languages. 
  From 1968 to 1970 Falbr was a member of the Communist Party 
of Czechoslovakia. From 1963 to 69 he taught Spain and English 
at the Interior Ministry's School of Languages. Falbr is 
married and has a son and a daughter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

