<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Signs Labor Law Amendment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Signs Labor Law Amendment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104120694 Prague CTK in English 1240 GMT 9 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 9 (CTK) -- President Vaclav Havel 
today signed the amendment to the labor law passed by the 
government last month, chairman of the Bohemian-Moravian Chamber 
of Trade Unions (CMKOS) Richard Falbr informed delegates of the 
First CMKOS Congress today. Jiri Sitler of the President's 
Office confirmed the information for CTK. 
  Sitler said the president would speak about his reasons for 
signing in more detail during his regular Sunday radio address 
tomorrow. 
  The congress had decided to ask President Vaclav Havel, 
through either a declaration, resolution or letter, not to sign 
the amendment into law. The deadline for signing the law was 
midnight tonight. 
  Frantisek Klima, chairman of the Union of Public Road 
Transportation, suggested the congress call a 10-15-minute 
general strike if Havel signed the law, but the new CMKOS 
chairman, Richard Falbr, rebuffed the idea, saying it was 
necessary as soon as possible "to establish order among 
ourselves." 
  "Don't expect this congress to call a general strike," he 
said. His words were met with applause from congress delegates. 
  Falbr said he had expected Havel to sign the law, since it 
would be difficult for him to defy the government coalition. 
  The parts of the amendment that most disturb the unions are 
those defining work agreements for fixed periods of time and 
regulating night shift work for pregnant women. On March 22, 
about 40,000 union members from throughout the country gathered 
on Prague's Old Town Square to protest the amendment. 
  Parliament passed the amendment the following day, vetoing 
all opposition amendments to the amendment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

