<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Justifies Signing Amendment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Justifies Signing Amendment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104132094 Prague CTK in English 1501 GMT 10 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Prague, April 10 (CTK) -- President Vaclav Havel 
did some explaining during his regular Sunday radio address 
today. He said that he had signed the new labor law amendment 
into law on Saturday because it did not hurt employees nor 
conflict with the Charter of Fundamental Rights and Freedoms or 
any international agreements. 
  He said he'd received numerous letters asking him not to 
sign 
the law "from various unions, the Helsinki Committee, and other 
institutions," but decided he "could sign this law with a clean 
and peaceful conscience." 
  Union objections, he said, would unleash "mistrust in the 
independence, self-awareness, and responsibility of people, of 
employees," and added that collective agreements between 
employees and employers existed to further protect workers' 
rights. 
  Havel also pointed out that this was the 17th amendment to 
the labor law overall and already the tenth since November 1989, 
"so that if this or that one doesn't pass the test, it can be 
changed with the help of more amendments." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

