<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dlouhy Expects Economic Growth in 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dlouhy Expects Economic Growth in 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0904155594 Prague CTK in English 1935 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0904155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brno, April 8 (CTK) -- In terms of the gross 
domestic product and industrial production, the Czech Republic 
has overcome "the biggest decline and we can basically speak of 
potential prospects of economic growth," Czech Minister of 
Industry and Trade Vladimir Dlouhy said today. 
  Taking part in a discussion meeting with university students 
in Brno, he said "the decline of GDP was 14.2 percent in 1991, 
7.1 percent in 1992 and 0.3 percent last year, while this year 
we expect growth of around 2 percent." 
  Dlouhy said that "we can expect inflation to be under 10 
percent" this year. He stressed that the Czech Republic in this 
point differed from other post-Communist economies, including 
Slovakia, Poland and Hungary. 
  Dlouhy also said that European Community countries had 20 
percent share in the Czech Republic's exports at the end of the 
1980s, while last year the figure was 55 percent and this year 
it may reach 60 percent. 
  He attributed the figures to the fact that a number of 
companies had managed to find new markets and at the same time 
penetrate "hard world markets, when the soft, socialist ones, 
simply disappeared." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8271 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu070__a94039" </HT>


<HEADER>
