<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Confidence in State Institutions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Confidence in State Institutions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104121294 Prague CTK in English 0853 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 11 (CTK) -- Confidence in the 
president, government, and parliament is stable, according to a 
March poll of 885 individuals by the Institute for Public 
Opinion Research (IVVM). 
  The poll showed 69 percent of respondents having confidence 
in President Vaclav Havel, the same percentage as in December 
1993 and three percent more than in January 1994. Confidence in 
the government registered at 57 percent in March, up from 56 in 
December and 53 in January. 
  Only 25 percent expressed confidence in parliament's work; 
still that was up from a mere 20 percent in December and 21 
percent in January. 
  The March poll also showed no difference in results between 
Bohemia and Moravia, or between cities and the countryside. 
Differences showed up between white and blue collar employees: 
The former generally expressed higher levels of confidence. 
  The greatest differences, however, showed up in a breakdown 
by respondents' political party affiliation. The greatest 
confidence in the president, government, and parliament was 
expressed by supporters of the (coalition) Civic Democratic 
Party (ODS), with 93, 87 and 44 percent respectively. The least 
confidence (23-18-2 percent) was expressed by Left Bloc (LB) and 
Communist Party (KSCM) voters. 
  In between, 77, 77, and 25 percent of voters for the 
(coalition) Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) expressed confidence 
in the three institutions, while confidence dropped to 44-37-15 
percent among voters for the Czech Social Democratic Party 
(CSSD). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8272 </DOCNO>
