<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wallis Sentenced for Selling Secret Information </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wallis Sentenced for Selling Secret Information </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804141194 Prague CTK in English 0708 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Plzen, April 8 (CTK) -- The Plzen district court 
today sentenced former Federal and Security Information Service 
(FBIS) employee Vaclav Wallis to 37 months' unconditional 
imprisonment for selling secret information from the FBIS to 
former Harvard Investment Funds director Viktor Kozeny. 
  The sentence is to be carried out in a prison with the 
second 
highest security level. The verdict has not yet taken effect, 
and the accused and the state attorney are still able to appeal 
against it. 
  Justifying the verdict, Judge Premysl Spicar said that by 
betraying state secrets in 1992, Wallis committed two crimes -- 
that of threatening state secrets and abusing public office. 
  Despite the objections of the defense, the court said Wallis 
was a public servant, although it did not uphold the claim of 
the prosecution that by abuse of public office Wallis had caused 
particularly serious consequences. Thus the court finally gave 
a lower sentence than that asked for by the state attorney, who 
in his closing speech had proposed that Wallis be imprisoned for 
6.5 years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

