<H3> <TI>   Finnish Deputies Discuss Security, `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finnish Deputies Discuss Security, `Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104201194 Prague CTK in English 1618 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1104201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 11 (CTK) -- Questions of economic 
integration and European security were the main topics discussed 
by visiting members of the Finnish Parliament's Foreign Affairs 
Committee and their Czech colleagues at their meeting today, 
Pertti Paasio, chairman of the Finnish Parliament's Foreign 
Committee, told CTK after the talks. 
  Paasio said that the Czech Republic, given its interest in 
joining NATO, had a somewhat different idea about its security 
than Finland, which did not see participation in a military 
grouping as its way to security. "The roles of our countries in 
the Partnership for Peace project are therefore somewhat 
different but the two countries will be complementing each 
other," he said. 
  Paasio said that within the Partnership Finland was sharing 
its experiences with United Nations peace-keeping operations but 
did not intend to participate in joint military exercises of the 
countries which participate in the project. 
  Paasio mentioned similar efforts of Finland and the Czech 
Republic at approaching the European Union (EU) and achieving 
full membership of European economic structures in the long run. 
He voiced the hope that trade between Finland and the Czech 
Republic would be more extended in the future that it has been 
before. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

