<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky Views NATO Actions in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jeszenszky Views NATO Actions in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204072194 Budapest MTI in English 2100 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204072194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 11 Apr (MTI) -- NATO's attacks against 
Serbian military positions in Gorazde served peace not war and 
the Bosnian Serbs will hopefully take the warning seriously 
enough to return to the negotiating table, Hungarian Foreign 
Minister Geza Jeszenszky told the press in Los Angeles today. 
  Hungary's involvement in controlling no-fly zones in Bosnia, 
which is based on a UN mandate, has to be separated from NATO 
actions in Sarajevo and Gorazde. The latter manoeuvres were 
governed by other Security Council resolutions, and had nothing 
to do with AWACS surveillance flights over Hungary, the minister 
said. 
  In reply to MTI, Jeszenszky said he welcomed all steps that 
promote a political solution and, at the same time, warn 
aggressive forces. 
  He expressed the hope that the action would contribute to a 
political settlement, which started with the Croat-Muslim 
agreement. 
  Asked about the position of the Russian government, 
Jeszenszky said Moscow had to be aware that such action might 
occur. 
  The minister expressed the hope that Moscow would continue 
to 
cooperate with the United States and the United Nations in 
settling the Yugoslav crisis. 
  He recalled that Russian policy had played a useful role in 
Bosnian mediation over the past few months. He added that peace 
in Bosnia is as much a Russian interest as that of the Unites 
States, Hungary and Bosnia itself. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

