<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talbott Arrives, Meets With Offcials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talbott Arrives, Meets With Offcials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Partnership for Peace Discussed </H4>

<F P=102> LD1104214094 Warsaw PAP in English 1920 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1104214094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 11 -- Feasible cooperation between the 
Polish defence system and NATO is the most important issue. If 
that occures Poland's membership of NATO will be a formal 
confirmation of the existing state of affairs, Foreign Minister 
Andrzej Olechowski told journalists following Monday's meeting 
with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. 
  According to the Polish minister, the visit of Mr. Talbott 
in 
Poland has rather not changed anything in Polish-American 
relations. "I do not see substantial changes in relation to what 
I heard three months ago," Olechowski said. 
  He stressed that Polish presentation document stipulating 
proposals and possibilities for Poland's cooperation within the 
framework of the "Partnership for Peace" programme, to be 
presented soon, is being welcomed warmly. The minister said 
that Poland has various proposals of cooperation but declined to 
disclose details. He added that President Bill Clinton's July 
visit to Warsaw was also discussed at the Foreign Ministry. 
  Strobe Talbott, asked by journalists when Poland is to 
become 
NATO member, replied that the Partnership for Peace programme is 
a path leading to NATO and stressed the determination of the 
Polish side to actively participate in the programme. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

