<H3> <TI>   Walesa on Coalition, New Candidate for Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa on Coalition, New Candidate for Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104180394 Warsaw PAP in English 1403 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1104180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 11 -- Presidential press spokesman 
Andrzej Drzycimski said Monday that President Lech Walesa would 
be willing to meet representatives of the government coalition 
if a new candidate for the post of finance minister was put 
forward. 
  He added that the coalition should look at matters anew and 
consider a new approach to the problem of who is to replace 
Marek Borowski as finance minister. President Walesa has 
already refused to accept the candidacy of Dariusz Rosati from 
Premier Waldemar Pawlak. 
  Asked whether Walesa had finally decided whether or not to 
sign the budget law, Drzycimski replied, "The president still 
has time for this under the Constitution, he is considering the 
matter." 
  According to the "small" interim Constitution the president 
signs a law within 30 days after it has been presented to him 
having been passed by both houses of parliament. According to 
Andrzej Gliniecki from the legal office at the president's 
chancellery, the budget law was presented to Walesa on March 28. 

</TEXT>

