<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. General Continues Visit, Talks on NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. General Continues Visit, Talks on NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Vacaroiu, Joulwan Discuss Army Issues </H4>

<F P=102> AU0704065194 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1526 GMT 6 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704065194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES, 6/4/1994 -- American General 
George Joulwan, Supreme Commander of the Allied Forces of 
Europe, said on 6 April in Bucharest that there was clear will 
with the NATO to back Romania and the Partnership for Peace 
would be paralleled by a "Partnership for Prosperity", the two 
elements being considered as guarantees of lasting stability. 
The general, now on a visit in Romania, met with Prime Minister 
Nicolae Vacaroiu. 
  The main issue discussed was Romania's adhesion to the 
Partnership for Peace and the prospects of the country's full 
integration in the Euro-Atlantic structures. The Romanian 
premier stressed that Romania's foreign policy laid stress on 
the development of the relations with the NATO and all its 
member states, an orientation backed by all political forces of 
the country. Referring to the military domain, the premier 
integrated the specialty problems in the general picture of the 
country's economic situation, stressing that, although 
administrating an austerity budget, the Romanian Government was 
ready to back financially, more than in the past years, the 
process of reorganization and updating of the Army. 
  "The main issue the Army is facing is the lack of financial 
resources and specialty technical assistance, domains in which 
the NATO support would be very efficient," the Romanian premier 
added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

