<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Considers Postponing Local Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Considers Postponing Local Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804200594 Prague CTK in English 1544 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 8 (CTK) -- The Slovak Government 
is considering the postponement of local elections, Prime 
Minister Jozef Moravcik said at the 4th congress of the 
Association of Slovak Towns and Villages (ZMOS) today. 
  Parliament Chairman Ivan Gasparovic supported the stance, 
explaining that the parliament would not probably be capable of 
discussing a bill on changes in the organization of local and 
state administration. The local elections are scheduled to take 
place in the autumn. 
  President Michal Kovac pointed out that no essential 
progress 
in the reform of state administration had been made since the 
past local elections held in 1990, when the system of national 
committees was abolished. 
  ZMOS Chairman Michal Sykora, delivering a report on the ZMOS 
activity, stressed the need to ratify the European Charter of 
local administration. 
  He added the previous government could not ratify it because 
of legislation differences. But the parliament has recommended 
to the new government to prepare necessary documents for the 
ratification of the Charter which has been signed by the three 
other Visegrad Four countries -- the Czech Republic, Hungary and 
Poland. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

