<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ZRS Leader Comments on Privatization, Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ZRS Leader Comments on Privatization, Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204101294 Prague CTK in English 2036 GMT 11 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 11 (CTK) -- The Slovak Workers' 
Association (ZRS), a newcomer to the Slovak political scene, 
came fourth in March popularity polls of political parties, 
Slovak Radio said today. Over five percent of the respondents 
preferred the ZRS. 
  The news has aroused foreign interest, as evidenced by 
today's talks between ZRS Chairman Jan Luptak and British 
Ambassador in Slovakia David Bright. 
  Speaking on the radio, Luptak said Bright had been 
interested 
by the (blue collar) workers' negative attitude to market 
economy being introduced throughout Slovakia. [sentence as 
received] 
  "It is impossible to privatize quickly and at the same time 
justly," Luptak said, pointing to the privatization of British 
Rail, whose privatization he said has been going on for twenty 
years despite Britain having a healthier economy (than Slovakia). 
  "The ZRS has made contacts with the international workers' 
movement and is especially interested in the policy of the 
Norwegian Workers' Party which won the latest elections," Luptak 
said. 

</TEXT>

