<H3> <TI>   Kanis, Polish Counterpart Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kanis, Polish Counterpart Discuss Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0904155494 Prague CTK in English 1945 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0904155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Poprad, east Slovakia, April 8 (CTK) -- The 
cooperation of the Visegrad Four countries in the military 
sphere, their admission into Western military systems and 
modernization of the Slovak and Polish armed forces were 
discussed by Slovak and Polish Defense Ministers Piotr 
Kolodziejczyk and Pavol Kanis today. 
  Kolodziejczyk told journalists he was optimistic regarding 
regional cooperation of the Central European countries and the 
Partnership for Peace project. This is a way of creating a 
joint defense area which has no alternative, he added. 
  Kanis (left-orientated Democratic Left Party, SDL, appointed 
to the post on March 16) said that Slovakia's orientation 
towards the West would continue. This is evidenced by the 
identical view of the ministers that the Visegrad Four countries 
(Slovakia, Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic) should enter 
NATO jointly, he added. 
  Kolodziejczyk said the Polish offer to jointly use military 
training areas, including that above the Baltic Sea, was still 
topical and it was being discussed by experts. 
  Poland is planning a string of joint military exercises with 
NATO countries. It would like Visegrad Four representatives to 
participate as observers, Kolodziejczyk said. Kanis added that 
the exchange of smaller units had been proposed as well. 

</TEXT>

