<H3> <TI>   Klaus Denies Controversy in Talks With Pawlak </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Denies Controversy in Talks With Pawlak </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304085094 Prague CTK in English 1943 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1304085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 12 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav 
Klaus said on Czech Radio today that no controversial themes 
came up during his meeting with Polish Premier Waldemar Pawlak 
in the Polish province of Jelenia Gora on Sunday [10 April]. 
  Asked if during the almost five hours of discussion between 
the chairman of "one of the few genuinely right-wing parties in 
Europe and the leader of the post-communist Polish People's 
Party" there reigned only harmony and agreement, Czech Premier 
Vaclav Klaus said he would be "more careful about using these 
easy labels such as post-communist," because the world was 
always a little bit more complicated. He had talked to Pawlak 
about completely specific things, in the realization of which 
both countries were interested. "Thus I do not think there was 
any room, essentially, for disagreement on such matters," Klaus 
said. 
  He said that Poland, at least according to Pawlak, did not 
have differing foreign policy ambitions. However, Klaus said it 
was not impossible that if he had spoken to President Lech 
Walesa or Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski, the difference in 
opinion on some things might have been greater. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

