<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nastase, Hungarian Deputies Discuss Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nastase, Hungarian Deputies Discuss Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204181694 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1501 GMT 12 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES, 12/4/1994 -- "I am coming to 
Bucharest with an open heart and with optimistic plans. Both 
countries need to cross the threshold of conciliation and, 
moreover, of cooperation, and I hope that in future our peoples 
will work together in friendship," said Imre Pozsgay, president 
of the Democrats' National Alliance of Hungary [MDSZ] on the eve 
of his delegation's visit to Romania. 
  "As far as the Romanian-Hungarian relations are concerned, I 
also wish to add that MDSZ, which the forthcoming elections are 
very likely to usher into parliament, is pursuing a foreign 
policy based on understanding, not on [word indistinct] looking 
back into the past. Only a foreign policy looking ahead at the 
future stands the chance of forging the conditions of 
cooperation between our countries in a united Europe," the 
president of the Democrats' National Alliance of Hungary also 
said. 
  MDSZ President Imre Pozsgay arrived in Bucharest today for a 
visit to Romania. 
  Adrian Nastase, speaker of the Chamber of Deputies, received 
Tuesday, April 12, a Hungarian parliamentary delegation, led by 
independent deputy Imre Pozsgay, co-chairman of the Democrats' 
National Alliance of Hungary. 
  Adrian Nastase and Imre Pozsgay reviewed the political, 
economic and social evolutions in Romania and Hungary in the 
past four years. It was stressed that it was important for the 
two countries to have normal, good neighborliness relations, 
with stress being laid on the necessity to increase economic 
links. 
  Adrian Nastase mentioned that it was essential that 
psychological barriers be overcome, for the progress the two 
parties intend to be put in place in point of their relations. 
  The Hungarian parliamentary delegation had interviews 
Tuesday, April 12, with leaders of the parliamentary groups in 
the Chamber of Deputies, with members of the Foreign Policy 
Commission. The two parties showed willingness to establish 
good neighborly links, to support each other in the two 
countries' activity in international bodies. 
  Imre Pozsgay expressed total confidence in an exemplary 
solution to the problems still causing divergencies. "Our common 
interests are more powerful than our divergencies and all means 
have to be found to pull down existing barriers." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8337 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu071__a94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-071-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Minister Meets With Iliescu, Vacaroiu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colombian Minister Meets With Iliescu, Vacaroiu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204074094 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1634 GMT 11 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 11/4/1994 -- Romanian President 
Ion Iliescu received Monday, April 11, Colombian Foreign 
Minister Noemi Sanin Posada. The stage of Romanian-Colombian 
ties was examined, the way in which projects were fulfilled 
agreed on in the summer of 1993, when Romania's president paid a 
visit to Colombia. 
  The interview occasioned talks on bilateral projects of 
interest and an exchange of opinions on the situation in 
Romania's area. Colombia is interested to enter the 
East-European economic market. President Ion Iliescu spoke to 
the Colombian guest about the economic prospects of his country 
for the period to come. 
  The agreements of scientific and cultural cooperation 
between 
Romania and Colombia are to be followed by commercial, 
interbanking and air transport accords, that are going to 
complete the legal framework necessary for the development of 
bilateral links, Romanian Premier Nicolae Vacaroiu and Colombian 
Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin Posada showed in their Monday, 
April 11 interview. 
  The prime minister proposed, in the presence of Romania's 
Foreign Minister Teodor Melescanu, that a Chamber of Commerce be 
set up in the month of May, when the Colombian minister of trade 
is scheduled to visit Bucharest, with a view to turn to good 
account projects that have already been sketched, such as the 
production in Romania of sugar and juices. 
  Mrs. Sanin specified that her people was viewing Romania as 
its closest friend in this geographic area. She opined that 
Romania could become one of the main distributors of Colombian 
products in Europe, that a swap of experience and cooperation 
between the two sides could be beneficial for both of them. 
  Premier Vacaroiu was pleased to accept the invitation to 
make 
a visit to Colombia, extended by Foreign Minister Sanin. 
  The minister of foreign relations of the Republic of 
Colombia, Noemi Sanin Posada ended Monday, 11 April, her 
official visit to Romania. On leaving, Mrs. Posada told the 
press that her visit had excellent results, and that her talks 
with the Romanian officials were extremely productive. 
  The Romanian-Colombian cooperation must be boosted mostly in 
what economic ties are concerned, the chief of the Colombian 
diplomacy said, and said her country's minister of foreign trade 
was to visit Romania soon. "We want to import from Romania as 
many cars and steel products as possible, and hope that 
companies in our countries go into closer relations," she said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

