<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister Calls For Support </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Prime Minister Calls For Support </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204195994 Prague CTK in English 1848 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 12 (CTK) -- Slovak Deputy Premier 
Brigita Schmognerova today in an address to parliament asked for 
support from deputies and citizens for the tough measures her 
government was going to pursue in order to make up for 
ex-premier Meciar government's mistakes. 
  "The government has not taken over an easy heritage," said 
Schmognerova at today's parliamentary debate on the government 
programme. 
  She said that in addition to economic recession and the 
breakup of the federation, the previous cabinets incompetence 
and hindrance of reforms were to blame for the bad state of the 
Slovak economy. 
  As a result, gross domestic product fell last year by 4.1 
percent, industrial production by 13.5 percent and construction 
work by 25 percent. Slovakia's foreign trade deficit was nearly 
27 billion crowns, the state sector's debt reached 60 billion 
crowns and prices grew by 23 percent. Fifty-seven percent of 
all enterprises were loss-making. 
  "This government could have chosen the easier path of 
preserving the present status quo without the unpleasant impact 
of unpopular measures, whereby it would have achieved a good 
pre-election position," said Schmognerova. 
  She stressed that reaching the government's stated goals -- 
approaching zero GDP growth, a 10-13 percent inflation rate, 
unemployment below 17 percent and a budget deficit below four 
percent -- would be very complicated and would require public 
support. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

