<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Calls on Council Chairmen To Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Calls on Council Chairmen To Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304081394 Prague CTK in English 1934 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1304081394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 12 (CTK) -- The Slovak Government 
of Premier Jozef Moravcik today called on the chairmen of 
several district councils to leave their offices. 
  Several days after Slovak President Michal Kovac's address 
in 
parliament, considered to be the start of the process which led 
to the dismissal of Vladimir Meciar's cabinet, 17 district 
council chairmen and two government commissioners signed a 
statement accusing the president of "gross insult to 
parliamentary democracy." They said Kovac deliberately 
destabilized the political scene and discredited Meciar's 
government in his speech. 
  "The district council chairmen who signed the statement 
violated the professional honor and committed a serious offense 
incompatible with the exercising of high administrative 
functions," Slovak Deputy Premier Ivan Simko told journalists 
today after the cabinet meeting. 
  Moravcik's government believed that after taking the office 
it provided these district council chairmen enough time to 
apologies to President Kovac and to reassess their stand, 
Finance Minister Rudolf Filkus said. "This is a moral appeal and 
not an appeal for political reasons," he added. 
  Asked if controls of district councils' activities could be 
expected Simko said that the government had ordered internal 
controls in all branches including the central state 
administration bodies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

