<H3> <TI>   Coexistence Deputy Views Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coexistence Deputy Views Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204172694 Prague CTK in English 1325 GMT 12 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1204172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 12 (CTK) -- "If the government 
treats us correctly we will never betray it," Stefan Harna, a 
deputy from Egyutteles (Coexistence), a Hungarian minority 
movement in Slovakia, told journalists today. 
  Duka-Zolyomi, chairman of the Egyutteles deputies' group, 
added that the movement's cooperation with the new government 
had been good thus far. Hungarian minority parties had had an 
opportunity to participate in the coalition council's talks when 
the government's programme was drafted and Hungarian deputies 
would therefore support the programme, Harna said. 
  Harna was reacting to information that some Hungarian 
deputies would allegedly not support the programme. Deputy Erno 
Rozsa condemned efforts to place Hungarian parties once more in 
the role of enemy. 
  Harna said Hungarian parties, through no fault of their own, 
had found themselves in a position in which their votes would 
decide the future of the current Slovak Government. 
  Rozsa noted that the current election law was adequate as it 
ensured calling early elections and that there was in fact 
nothing to change in it. The law guarantees the right of ethnic 
minorities' representatives to enter parliament and defend their 
rights. 

</TEXT>

