<H3> <TI>   Pursuit of Russian Arms Purchases Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pursuit of Russian Arms Purchases Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304101094 Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA in Romanian 8 Apr 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1304101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Oana Stanciulescu: "Russia Will Continue To </F>
Deliver Arms to Romania"] 
  [Text] On the occasion of the visit that Russian General 
Pavel Grachev paid to Bucharest, Romania and Russia agreed to 
continue with the delivery of spare parts for the three types of 
military technology in which we are still dependent on the 
ex-Soviet industry, namely radar, air-to-air missiles, and air 
force, government sources informed us. However, Russia was not 
successful in its efforts to sell us artillery technology and 
armored vehicles. As far as armored vehicles are concerned, 
General Grachev was taken to witness a military drill of an 
armored unit to shatter any illusions he nurtured in this area. 
  Nevertheless, Romania shows interest in purchasing air force 
equipment. Romania is counting on the McConnel Amendment to the 
draft federal budget of the United States for 1995, which 
represents the legal basis for loans and military assistance 
promised to our country by the United States when Romania joined 
the Partnership for Peace. 

</TEXT>

