<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croat Negotiator Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croat Negotiator Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204192694 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting between a delegation of the Republic of 
Croatia and a delegation of the Serbs living in the UN-protected 
areas should have been held in Zagreb today. The meeting had 
been agreed upon in principle back on 29 March when the 
cease-fire agreement was signed. The new meeting should have 
been devoted to the normalization of the situation in the sphere 
of economy. 
  Despite an intervention by the mediators of the Zagreb 
negotiations, the Serb delegation did not come to the meeting 
today, probably because of the confusing situation prevailing in 
those areas, particularly now that they are constituting their 
new leadership. This was stated by Hrvoje Sarinic, head of the 
Croatian delegation to negotiations with the local Serbs. He 
added: I would like to recall that the cease-fire agreement is 
only a part of a project of normalization of overall relations 
throughout the Republic of Croatia, not a sort of a settlement 
between the Republic of Croatia and the UN-protected areas. 
Further negotiations will refer to economic issues and the 
final political solution within the internationally recognized 
borders of the Republic of Croatia. It is under these 
conditions and with the guarantees by the United States, Russia, 
the European Union, and the United Nations that we agreed to 
hold Zagreb negotiations and sign the agreement itself. 
  The Republic of Croatia is, as it has always been, 
interested 
in the resumption of negotiations leading to the complete 
normalization of relations and we are expressing our readiness 
that these negotiations could continue anywhere on the territory 
of the Republic of Croatia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

