<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Compared to Hungarian Counterpart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Compared to Hungarian Counterpart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304102094 Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK in Slovak 8 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU1304102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "kn": "The Army of the Slovak Republic Will </F>
Survive, but...."] 
  [Text] Major General Andrej Sabol, state secretary at the 
Ministry of Defense of the Slovak Republic, stated yesterday 
that, in dividing the CSFR Army, we performed "the largest peace 
operation in Europe." Out of 7,000 professional soldiers of 
Slovak nationality, some 5,000 have stayed on the territory of 
the Czech Republic for various reasons. According to Sabol, the 
Army, too, suffers from a shortage of money, but "our arms 
systems will survive until approximately 2015." It is not true 
that the Army of the Slovak Republic is weaker than Hungary's. 
Slovakia abides by the international agreements on troop 
numbers and armaments, and its compliance with those agreements 
is being regularly monitored. Our involvement in the Partnership 
for Peace is not conditional on the compatibility of our arms 
systems. What must be common, however, is the method of 
communication. The prerequisite for this is command of the 
English language, which is still a problem for our Army. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

