<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   SNF Calls For `Voluntary' Armed Units </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SNF Calls For `Voluntary' Armed Units </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204144194 Bratislava SME in Slovak 8 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1204144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SME </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Eva Cobejova: "What Is Hidden Behind One Post </F>
Office Box"] 
  [Text] The weekly ZMENA [Change] has presented to the 
Slovak youth an offer to become involved in the activity of the 
Slovak National Front (SNF). We do not learn from the quite 
extensive article who specifically stands behind this 
initiative. The address, a post office box in Trnava, does not 
reveal much. What does the front actually offer us? To build 
on the "traditions of healthy patriotism and Christian ethics." 
The aim is to "make the political and economic leadership of 
the state respect the interests of the nation and protect its 
freedom.... On no account do we intend to stand idly by and 
watch the cryptocommunists in parliament and in the Slovak 
Government sell our homeland to the political-criminal 
underworld and the international mafia." The SNF will be 
against foreigners being given jobs in Slovakia and foreign-made 
goods penetrating our market. The SNF calls for a "morally pure 
government, supported by a potent Army, the police, and 
voluntary units of armed citizens in the style of the National 
Guard." Hidden behind the anonymous post office box in Trnava 
are thus new armed units that want to defend this nation, 
whether we want it or not. Does this not remind you by chance of 
some organizations from Slovak history, about which a judge of 
the Slovak Supreme Court recently said that these were "good 
organizations, which were only misused by politicians"? Who 
will misuse the SNF? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8377 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu071_y_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-071 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Meets With Akashi, Condemns Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Milosevic Meets With Akashi, Condemns Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304121594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1136 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 13 Apr (TANJUG) -- This morning, Serbian 
President Slobodan Milosevic received Yasushi Akashi, head of 
the UN mission in former Yugoslavia, and colleagues. 
  During the talks, which covered the latest developments in 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina, President Milosevic said that by 
bombing Serb positions, the United Nations has abandoned the 
principles of impartiality vis-a-vis the warring sides in the 
civil war in Bosnia-Herzegovina and openly sided with the 
Muslims. This has seriously brought into question the trust 
required for the realization of its role as mediator in the 
negotiating process in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The Serbian president pointed to the fact that the offensive 
by the Muslim forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina has been going on for 
a long time now, and that Gorazde's position as a so-called safe 
zone, in full view of UN representatives, has been abused by the 
Muslim forces, allowing them to concentrate on their offensive 
against the Serbs. 
  The United Nations has neither prevented, nor hindered these 
attempts but, on the contrary, has supported them in terms of 
direct military involvement, something the Serb nation and the 
Serb Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina condemns energetically. In 
the view of President Milosevic, this behavior is not in the 
interest of peace but prolongs the war and intensifies 
instability in this region. 
  In President Milosevic's opinion, the only real way out of 
the current situation is to achieve a general agreement on the 
cessation of all hostilities. 
  A peace agreement should be reached as soon as possible 
without prejudging the political solution, President Milosevic 
stressed, pointing out his belief that the Serb side will accept 
new negotiations without preconditions after a cessation of all 
hostilities is in place. However, this can be done only on an 
equal footing. This means that the sanctions should be lifted. 
If the international community sincerely wants peace then it 
should respect the principle of equality. Sanctions imposed 
against Serbia and the Serb nation represent a constant impetus 
for the Bosnian authorities to continue the war. That is why 
lifting the embargo is the simplest way to make the Bosnian 
authorities abandon their war policy. 
  Yasushi Akashi agreed with the assessment that an agreement 
on a general cessation of hostilities is better than a partial 
one because it ensures the best conditions for the resumption 
and successful conduct of political negotiations based on the 
principle of the equality of all three sides. 
  Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic also attended 
the talks, the statement issued by the Serbian president's 
office says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

