<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tasks for New Committee of Defense Affairs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tasks for New Committee of Defense Affairs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1204190894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government has decided to set up a committee for 
defense affairs attached to the Council of Ministers. The new 
committee will be chaired by the prime minister, with the 
minister of national defense as his deputy. Committee members 
include deputy prime ministers, the ministers of internal 
affairs, foreign affairs, finance, industry, and foreign 
economic cooperation, and the heads of the Council of Ministers 
Office and the Central Planning Office. 
  According to National Defense Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk, 
the committee should, above all, deal with reforming the command 
structures to bring them closer to West European standards. 
  [begin Kolodziejczyk recording] In brief, it will mean the 
departure from the existing command structures, the setting up 
of the post of the commander in chief of the Polish Army, and 
land, air, and naval forces commanders subordinated to him. 
  The next important issue the committee should deal with is 
to 
put in order the legal foundations for the functioning of the 
ministry and the Army. Here I would give priority to the deep 
and long-ranging amendments to the law on the public defense 
duty, which first of all should introduce a division of powers 
between the civilian minister of national defense and the 
commander in chief, or, for the time being, the head of the 
General Staff of the Polish Army. It is also necessary to 
regulate a number of other matters, which are outdated in the 
present reality and are even hampering all progress. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

