<H3> <TI>   Akashi, Lapresle Fail To Meet With Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akashi, Lapresle Fail To Meet With Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204183194 Paris AFP in English 1800 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1204183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, April 12 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs 
retaliating against NATO air strikes placed at least 40 UN 
observers under house arrest Tuesday, a UN official said, 
severing lines of communication with peacekeeping authorities. 
[passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile the United Nations special representative in 
former 
Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, was thwarted in a bid to 
re-establish contact with Bosnian Serb leaders at their Pale 
stronghold near the Bosnian capital. 
  After a meeting earlier with Bosnian President Alija 
Izetbegovic, Akashi said he and the UN Protection Force's 
(UNPROFOR) overall commander, General Bertrand de Lapresle, were 
seeking an urgent meeting with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic. 
  But Akashi and De Lapresle left Sarajevo for Zagreb Tuesday 
afternoon after failing to reach Pale. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

