<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Says Serbs Trying To Reclaim Weapons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Says Serbs Trying To Reclaim Weapons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304140094 Paris AFP in English 1350 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 13 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb soldiers 
have tried to reclaim heavy weapons placed earlier this year 
under UN control, UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) spokesman Rob 
Annink said Wednesday [13 April]. 
  He said the soldiers tried to take the weapons Tuesday in 
Krivoglavci, northwest of Sarajevo, and withdrew after receiving 
orders from their command post in Lukavica which had been 
contacted by the UNPROFOR. 
  The weapons were placed under UN control following a 
February 
accord between Bosnian Serbs and Moslems on an immediate 
ceasefire and the withdrawal of heavy weapons from around the 
capital Sarajevo. 
  The agreement was prompted by a NATO ultimatum to Serb and 
Moslem units to remove artillery pieces to sites outside a 
20-kilometre (12-mile) radius or face air strikes. 
  Annink said that following the recent NATO air raids against 
Serbian position in the Moslem enclave of Gorazde, Serb troops 
have placed mines around three of the weapons collection sites 
thus blocking the UN personnel guarding the sites. 
  He added that the UNPROFOR is also unaware of the 
whereabouts 
of a UN military observer and his Serb interpreter who 
disappeared two days ago after leaving the Moslem enclave of 
Zepa. 
  He said attempts to get information about the pair from 
Bosnian Serb authorities have been unsuccessful. 
  Annink said that 58 other UN military observers have been 
blocked in Serb-held territory since the NATO raids Sunday and 
Monday. 
  He said some of the observers are considered hostages while 
others have been allowed limited freedom of movement. They 
include observers based in Lukavica, near Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

