<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mladic Orders Troops To Down NATO Aircraft </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mladic Orders Troops To Down NATO Aircraft </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1204144094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1204144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mirjana Kusmuk] </F>
  [Text] After his meeting with Russian special envoy 
Vitaliy Churkin, at which they discussed the situation in 
Gorazde following NATO's air intervention, Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the Srpska republic, visited Serbian fighters on 
the Gorazde front. At the headquarters of the Serbian army in 
Rogatica, general Ratko Mladic, commander of the general staff 
of the army of Srpska republic, submitted a report to Karadzic 
on the military situation on the ground. 
  The president of the Srpska republic then visited the 
positions of the Serbian army and the command of the Gorazde 
brigade. In conversations with the soldiers, Karadzic stressed 
that the United Nations and General Rose bear the sole 
responsibility for the bombing of the Serbian civilian targets 
around Gorazde, and that they have taken sides with one side in 
the civil war in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  We are constantly being threatened with bombing. They have 
now played this card. The only thing left for them to do is to 
send ground forces. You here are more superior. You are not 
the bare- footed Somalians, but are currently the best army in 
Europe, Karadzic said. 
  General Mladic expressed the view that there will be more 
air 
strikes. He said that the army's morale is exceptional and that 
the general command of the Srpska republic has issued the order 
to all soldiers to shoot down whatever flies toward them. 
  UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] has been providing logistics 
support and giving advice to the Muslims and Croats for two 
years. They have now removed their mask and placed themselves on 
their side. Our only strategy is to defend our hearths, the 
weak, and our territory, General Mladic said. The president and 
the general also played a chess game on the first line of the 
front. 
  The Rogatica part of the Gorazde front is quiet today. Owing 
to poor weather, the Muslim soldiers have reduced their attacks. 
NATO aircraft are also affected by fog and rain and are today 
flying unusually high. 

</TEXT>

