<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Ukrainian Peacekeepers To Arrive </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More Ukrainian Peacekeepers To Arrive </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304072794 Paris AFP in English 0053 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304072794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, April 12 (AFP) -- Ukrainian 
peacekeepers are to begin arriving in Bosnia on Monday [18 
April] to be deployed in Gorazde, a UN spokesman said Tuesday 
[12 April]. 
  Fred Eckhard said the 550 troops will travel by different 
means to Sarajevo and their arrivals will be staggered. 
  Some 220 will fly to Bosnia between April 18 and 21, while 
330 will travel by train with military equipment, Eckhard said. 
  He did not say when they would leave Sarajevo for Gorazde 
but 
Colin Keating, who holds the rotating Security Council 
presidency, said it would be as soon as possible. 
  Ukraine has already sent 710 peacekeepers to Bosnia and 
Eckhard did not rule out the possibility that additional troops 
could be deployed in Gorazde where there are already a dozen UN 
military observers. 
  Keating indicated that as many as 1,000 could be sent. 

</TEXT>

