<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic, Greek Foreign Minister Meet in Athens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Granic, Greek Foreign Minister Meet in Athens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304115994 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1100 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Athens by correspondent Andjelko Perincic] </F>
  [Excerpts] Dr. Mate Granic and Karolos Papoulias, the 
foreign ministers of Croatia and Greece, agree that there is 
great scope for the comprehensive development of relations, 
especially economic relations, between the two countries. 
  Minister Granic, who arrived in Athens from Ankara this 
morning, had private talks for longer than expected with his 
counterpart and host, Papoulias. Afterwards they were joined by 
other members of the delegations and after the talks which are 
now over, and which lasted several hours, the two ministers 
spoke to journalists. [passage omitted] 
  The Croatian minister assessed that Greece could play a 
positive role in the peace process. This relates above all to 
the implementation of the Washington agreement and the inclusion 
of the Serbs in the negotiations on a federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The EU, currently presided over by Greece, 
should play a more active role in this process. [passage 
indistinct] 

</TEXT>

