<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Prepares Topics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Prepares Topics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304152894 Prague CTK in English 1434 GMT 13 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1304152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 13 (CTK) -- President Vaclav Havel 
told journalists today that he had prepared four broad topics 
for discussion during the meeting of the seven Central European 
presidents on Saturday [16 April] and Sunday in the east 
Bohemian town of Litomysl. 
  The first topic Havel proposes is the question of 
cooperation 
in Central Europe, the definition of the Central European space 
and the discussion of its character and prospects. 
  The second is the context of Central Europe in Europe 
itself. 
Theme three, Havel said, is Russia and the Balkans, because 
every discussion of Europe has to include these regions. 
Lastly, the present state of Europe, its problems, tasks, the 
dangers it faces and the prospects of its integration. 
  The main significance of the event, however, will be the 
opportunity it presents for informal discussions, during which 
differences of opinion need not be harmful, he said. 
  The six presidents Havel will be playing host to are from 
Slovakia, Austria, Hungary, Slovenia, Poland and Germany. 
Although Germany has only got "one foot" in Central Europe, as 
Havel said, its president, Richard von Weizsacker, was in office 
during Germany's reunification and several other moments crucial 
for Central Europe. Germany's participation may also help the 
country to formulate its relationship with its immediate eastern 
neighbors, he said. 
  Havel said he hoped the location of the meeting would 
contribute to the renewal of the spirit of regionalism which 
characterized the Czech lands in the time before communism, when 
the Czech republic became "just Prague and its surroundings". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

