<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac: Meciar's Methods `Dangerous,' `Harmful' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kovac: Meciar's Methods `Dangerous,' `Harmful' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404093694 Prague CTK in English 2042 GMT 13 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1404093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague/Bratislava, April 13 (CTK) -- "If in the 
future Vladimir Meciar ever headed the Slovak government I would 
consider it dangerous for Slovakia," Slovak President Michal 
Kovac said on Czech television this evening. 
  If the man ousted from the Slovak premiership by a March 
no-confidence vote were to become premier again, it "would only 
serve to strengthen Meciar's exceptional, almost superhuman 
abilities," Kovac said in an interview on the programme "21". 
  Meciar's style, methods and means had threatened Slovakia's 
interests. He had not managed to solve economic problems which 
in normal circumstances could have been solved, Kovac said. 
  "We were aware citizens were losing faith in politics and 
public servants, people's dissatisfaction was growing and ideas 
were entering their heads of the need for a strong hand and an 
authoritarian regime -- ideas far from the democratic style of 
government," he said. 
  Most of the original supporters of Meciar's party, the 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), and many members of 
parliament had realized the danger and harmfulness of Meciar's 
ways, Kovac said. 

</TEXT>

